{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958041101/0225.xml":{"full_text":"6\n\nof\ncEDERATOA\nQe\nst\n\nn\no\nZ\nAFL\n--CIO\ne\ns\nV*\nt\nZ\n9\n.7 M Rte.\nDUSTRIAL\n7o\"\n0Y\n/N\n1\nOfficial Newspaper Of\nToledo Industrial\nUnion Council\nTOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nA\nT H E O N L Y LA\nC\n[%4)\nNE\nPE\n\n\nJU B LiSH ED EVER\nWEEK IN TOLEDO\n**s\ns As M.\n08-oce\n\nco s* a s\nwak 3 s*s**t*5***\nif? (JESNER\nsi;B\n**77\nasoannnnid\n\n6\n27\n\n23\n\nVOL. 16, NO. 15\nPublished By Organized Labor\n425 Winthrop St., Toledo, Ome\nTOLEDO, OHIO, FRIDAY, APRIL 11, 1958\nPAnvsei PUs co.\nA\nTOLEDO\n0\nC\nOf Over 31,000 Subscribers\nFrom 120 Area Plants\nMail Delivered To Homes\n66\nInquiring\nReporter\nDo you discuss the need or value of Labor\nLilians in your home?\u201d\nRidener\nt\nPerkins\nCora Ridener, 29 Irving St:\n\u201cYes. My husband works at\nMather Springs. We compare\nideas and opinions so that we\nmay better understand the union\nand the problems we face.\u201d\nCurtis Perkins, 435 Second St.:\n\u201cI argue about the union with\nmy uncle who works at DeVil\nbiss Co. He usually points out\nhow much stronger the union is\nat DeVilbiss. My contention is\nthat we at Industrial Finishers\nare a newly organized plant.\nGive us a chance. We will get\nthere.\u201d\npit\nOwad\nGroseck\nDella Mae Owad, 102 Merlin\nRd., Perrysburg: \u201cThere are\nsome things I don't understand\nabout unions. My husband be\nlongs to the union and usually\nhas the answers.\u201d\nFrank Groseck, 748 Nebraska\nAve.: \u201cNo because my wife never\nworked in any plant and there\nfore, she would not understand\nthe problems. However, she re\nspects my judgement. For ex\nample I told her of the strike in\n\"the downtown stores and not to\ncross the picket line. I know she\nwould not shop in stores that are\non strike.\u201d\nX'\nSawicki\nWygand\nDan Sawicki, 2251 Door St.:\n\u201cYes, the union protects my in\nterests and helps me make a bet\n438 Camp Applications In;\nCounselors Start Meetings\nAlthough the opening of the Local 12 Summer Camp\nseason is still some 10 weeks ago, proof that it\u2019s later than\nyou think comes in a report from Camp Director Dan Pilo\nseno that meetings for counselors have begun.\nThe meetings started last Thursday and will run for\nseven\nconsecutive\nweeks\nfrom 7 to 8 p.m. in Parlor H,\nLocal 12 Hall, 42 5 Win\nthrop St.\nThose interested in being\ncounselors during the 10-week\ncamp season are urged to attend\nthe Thursday meetings.\nInstruction is given in leader\nship, camping lore, handling of\nyoungsters, hygiene, the history\nand the needs and aims of Local\n12 Summer Camp in Sand Lake,\nMich\nApplications Increasing\nMeanwhile, Summer Camp\nSecretary Marian Spies reports\nthat applications are coming in\nmore steadily each week.\nSo far 438 youngsters have put\nin their claim to a week\u2019s stay\nin camp\u2014264 boys and 174\ngirls.\nWith the warmer weather and\nthe ending of the Easter recess,\nexperience shows reservations\nwill come in greater numbers\nfrom here on in.\nLocal 12 President Clem Hole\nwinski reminded campers that\nthose coming for the first time\nwill need a series of typhoid and\nanti-tetantas shots, while those\nter living. It is important for\nmy wife to recognize this. My\nwife's father belongs to a union.\nMy wife and I fully appreciate\nthe benefits we gained because\nof a union.\u201d\nHelen Wygand, 1658 Home\nstead: \u201cWe discuss the union\n\u2022quite frequently. My husband is\na millwright and belongs to Lo\ncal 1393 AFL. We both agree\nthat the union elevated the\nstandard of living for working\npeople.\u201d\ns 4\nWoosley\nS\n1\nHastings\nCarl Woosley, 2565 Kress St.:\n\u201cYes. My dad belongs to Local\n14, UAW. We talk about the\nunion, the current recession and\nthe insecurity. We do not agree\nthat higher wages brought on\nunemployment as stated in the\npublic press. The union brought\nthe people out of the last depres\nsion. It will be the union that\nwill bring us out of this one.\u201d\nAlbert Hastings, 1609 Macom\nber St.: \u201cI discuss the union at\nhome with my wife because the\nunion benefits all of us\u2014my wife\nand the three children. I encour\nage my wife to attend the union\nmeetings so that she may better\nunderstand the problems of what\nthe union is striving to do for\nworking people and how our\nenemies are trying to destroy\nthe labor movement in Ameri\nca.\u201d\nDetroit Firm\nGoes for UAW\nIn an election conducted by,\nthe National Labor Relations'\nBoard this week, the UAW:\nwon bargaining rights at the\nMarston Corporation, located on\nDetroit\u2019s east side.\nThe vote was 37 for the UAW\nand 7 for the Metal Processors\nUnion.\nThe successful organizational\ndrive was conducted by the staffs\nof UAW vice president Richard\nGosser, who is also director of\nthe union\u2019s Competitive Shops\nDepartment, and George Merrel\nli, co-director of the UAW Re-'\ngion 1A.\nreturning will need only a boost\ner shot. I\nApplications received so far,\naccount for nearly 20 per cent;\nof the reservations which, Presi\ndent Holewinski said, is on a par\nwith last year at this time.\nHowever, he reminded UAW\nmembers that last year camp\nreservations were about com-1\npleted a few weeks before the\nopening of camp. Applications\nare accepted on a first come,\nfirst served basis, and the soon\ner youngsters apply, the more\nfavorable are their chances for\ngetting the camping period they\ndesire.\nSo far the following applica\ntions for the various weeks have\nbeen received:\nBOYS\n1st week June 22\n2nd week June 29\n3rd week\n4th week\n5th week\n1st week\n2nd week\n3rd week\n4th week\nJuly 6\nJuly 13\nJuly 20\nGIRLS\nJuly 27\nAug. 3\n231\n441\n55\n86\n56\n62\n59\nAug. 10\n27\n16!\nAug. 17\n5th week Aug. 24 10\nThis Week in City Council:\nCouncil OK's UA wProposal\nTo Speed Public Works Plan\n(See text of Resolution on Pace 8)\nCity Council unanimously adopted a 2-pronged resolu\ntion, recommended by the UAW Educational League, calling\nupon the Federal Gobernment to make funds available im\nmediately for a comprehensive puplic works program, and\nto map plans for local projects which could be started when\nsuch funds are made avail\nable.\nCouncilman Michael Da\nmas took the lead in urging\nCouncil passage of the resolution\npointing out that over 20,000\npersons were out of work in\nthe city and action is needed to\nget them to work.\nFollowing passage of the reso\nlution, Vice Mayor Ollie Cze\nlusta called his public works\ncommittee together Wednesday\nto start planning local works\nprojects which could be begun\nonce Federal funds are made\navailable.\nThe first side affect of the\nresolution was Council approval\nto spend $25,000 to construct\nstorm sewers and roadways in\nForest Cemetery.\nComplaints Received\nCouncil had received many\ncomplaints of flooding ot the\nCemetery and of inconvenience\nand annoyance to those paying\nvisits. But up to now the Admini\nstration and Council had been\ni reluctant to spend any money\nto make the necessary improve\nments.\nHowever, Councilman Czelus\nta noted that an hour previously\nCouncil voted to speed local\nproject and said \u201cthis is a good\nplace to start.\u201d\nAccordingly, Council went\nalong taking about $6,000 from\nthe Dorr St. overpass funds and\nthe balance from the proposed\nWest Toledo sewer project.\nAlso speaking in favor of the\nUAW resolution was Councilman\nJ. B. Simmons, Jr., who urged\nthe mayor to form a committee\nof 'industrialists and labor lead\ners to plan public works pro\ngrams.\nReferring to the fact that\nabout 25,000 residents were un\nemployed or working short\nweeks, he declared this \u201cwould!\nbe positive action.\u201d\nAlthough\nhe\nvoted\nfor\nthe\nresolution, Councilman Max\nReddish expressed reluctance as\nserting he doesn\u2019t think \u201cthis\narea is a particularly distressed\none.\u201d\nBudget Review Asked,\nDrop in Income Cited\nDeclining city revenues as a\nresult of the recession brought\nfrom Councilman Joseph Scalzo\na request for Council to recon\nsider its budget finances.\nPointing to the 2-month opera\nting revenue report which\nshowed the city's revenues and\nincome payroll tax collections\nwere running below estimates,\nCouncilman Scalzo suggested a\nreview.\n\u25a0He cited that income tax col\nlections were $125,000 below\nestimates the first two months\nand for a year could total $750,\n000, and other funds were down\nanother $65,000.\n(The Journal carried a story\non declining city revenues in de\ntail in the March 28 issue).\nHowever, other Councilmen\nsuggested waiting a few months\nto see if any pick-up developed\nand said a review would be made\nthen.\nHugh McPhie, city finance di\nrector, told Council that it\nlooked like the 1958 budget esti\nmate of $8,500,000 in payroll in\ncome tax \u201clooked a little ambiti\nous,\u201d and expressed the opinion\nthat it will pass the $8-million\nmark.\n1\nVo\nVote Reminder\nThe 19th Constitutional\nConvention of the Ohio CIO\nCouncil and the First Con\nstitutional Convention of the\nOhio AFL-CIO will be in ses\nsion in Cleveland beginning\nthe week of May 5.\nThis is to remind those dele\ngates who will be away from\ntheir home towns at that time\nthat Primary voting day is\nMay 6 and they can pick up\nabsentee ballots at their i\nBoards of Elections now and\ncast their Primary ballot.\n90,000 Can\nGetSUB, Ohio\nCIO Claims\nAn estimated 90,000 laid-off\nworkers already would have\nbeen eligible to receive supple\nmental unemployment benefits\n(SUB), according to the Ohio\nCIO Council.\nThe Council also said that SUB\n.payments to that number of eli\ngible workers would be $1,624,\n018 a week but \u201cunfortunately\nthe state administration has fol\nlowed a policy of blocking such\npayments.\u201d\nThe SUB figures show how\nimportant the additional benefits\ncould be to the unemployed and\nto the economy, the Council\npointed out.\nj \u201cThe payment of more than\n$1,000,000 a week would not\nonly be a tremendous help to the\nunemployed but would give the\ngeneral economy a badly-needed\n'shot in the arm,\u201d the Council\nsaid.\nChecked With Unions\nI\nThe Council said it compiled\nthe figures from reports filed\nwith the Council by the various\nunions with SUB contracts.\nIt said it decided to make such\na survey after Administrator\nannounced that only 2 0,000\nworkers could receive SUB pay-\u2019\nments and that the payments\nwould total less than $500,000 a\nweek.\n\u201cSince Tichenor\u2019s statement\nwas an obvious attempt to play\n-down the importance of SUB\nland the significance of the Ad\nministration\u2019s policy against\nSUB, we decided to compile\n'more accurate. figures to show'\nhow much the state\u2019s policy was\nactually costing Ohio workers,\nand the economy,\u201d the Council1\nsaid.\nThe Council emphasized that\nits figures were not complete.\nLocal 12 Meeting\nScheduled Tonight\nThe regular monthly meet\ning of Local 12, UAW, will be\nheld Friday (April 11) at 8\np.m. in Parlor A, 425 Win\nthrop St.\nThe Board of Governors of\nLocal 12 Summer Camp will\nmeet at 7 p.m. in advance of\nthe Local 12 session.\nAFL-CIO Calls for Action:\n3-Point Program Urged For Recession Victims\nThe AFL-CIO has urged a\nthree-point program on Con\ngress to ease the back-breaking\nburden that has fallen on the\nunemployed.\nIn testimony before the House\nWays and Means Committee on\nthe Administration program for\nextending unemployment com\n42 411 fa\npensation payments through fed\neral loans to the states, Nelson\nH. Cruikshank, director of the\nAFL-CIO Dept, of Social Se\ncurity, proposed:\nI\u2014\n\u25a0Enactment o f t h e Ken\nnedy-McCarthy bill, which\nwould permanently liberalize\nthe unemployment compensa\ntion laws, and as an emer\ngency step, increase the\namount of benefits and their\nduration until the states can\npass laws meeting new federal\nstandards.\n9\u2014Establishment o f federal\n\u201crecovery benefits\u201d simi\nliar to unemployment compen\nsation benefits for the jobless\nwho are not covered but who\nhave records of recent em\nment.\n3\u2014Authorization o f federal\ngrants for general assist\nance to relieve those not eligi\nble for either unemployment\ncompensation or recovery\nbenefits.\nCruikshank voiced AFL-CIO\nendorsement of the Administra\ntion\u2019s emergency program. He\nCongress Seen Giving Top Priority\nTo Jobless Pay Bill, Public Works\n77.\n*3/Ds. M\nUNEMPLOYED NEEDY in St. Louis lined up by the hundreds to\nmake application for surplus food to be distributed to them. Regis\ntration scene shows the jobless giving the required information to\nvolunteer workers at registration desks. Many reported they had\nbeen without jobs since July and were living day by day.\nNLRB Decision Awaited\nIn Retail Clerks Dispute\n(Special to Union Journal)\nWASHINGTON\u2014The National Labor Relations Board,\nwhich heard oral arguments on the Lasalle strike this week,\nwill now have to decide if what is sauce for the goose is also\nsauce for the gander.\nThe NLRB permits a store or firm to pull out of an\nassociation for individual\nbargaining with the unions\ninvolved. The Retail Clerks\nare insisting on the same right\nin their relationship with Retail\nAssociates.\nClerks attorney Joe Finley\npointed out that the stores ad\nmitted the association, \u201clike the\nold grey mare isn\u2019t what she\nused to be,\u201d when they filed for\na management Taft-Hartley elec\ntion last Nov. 20 following the\nTiedtke settlement.\n(When Tiedtke's\ncame\nto\nterms, it pulled out of Retail\nAssociates leaving Lasalle's.\nLamson\u2019s and the Lion Store as\nmembers.)\nThe strike against Lasalle's\nstarted after all three stores re\nfused to meet with the Retail\nClerks for individual store bar\ngaining.\nUnion Can\u2019t Petition\nBoard rules against permitting\na union not in compliance with)\nthe Taft-Hartley oath and finan\ncial reports generally work in'\nI warned, however. that it con\nstitutes no \"substitute for basic\nimprovements\u201d needed in the\npresent law and envisioned in\nthe Kennedy-McCarthy bill.\nThree Basic Shortcomings\n\"The shortcomings of unem\nployment insurance are of three\nkinds,\u201d Cruikshank told the\ncommittee.\n\u201cFirst, benefits are being paid\nonly to 6 out of every 10 of the\nunemployed. Second, workers\nfortunate enough to draw bene-!\nfits are averaging less than $30\na week; benefits average only\nabout one-third of past weekly!\nearnings. Third, about 40,000\nclaimants each week are using\nup the last of their benefits.\n\"Taking the exclusions, the\nexhaustions and the low bene\nfit levels into account, unem\nployment compensation is re\nturning to the economy less\nthan 17 per cent of the\ntotal\nwages lost. Because of this\nloss to our national purchas\ning power, these hearings are\nconcerned not only with the\nplight of the laidoff worker,\nbut also with the plight of his\nbutcher, his grocer and his\nlandlord.\u201d\nCruikshank pointed out that\nmore than 800.000 jobless work\ners have exhausted their bene\nfits since September. Some 3.3\nmillion unemployed who are,\nnow drawing benefits\u2014at rates,1\nvarying from state to state\u2014face\nmanagement's favor. Unions in\nthis position cannot petition for\nan NLRB-conducted election.\nRetail Clerks Locals 833 and\n128 have deliberately gotten out\nlof compliance to prevent an elec\ntion. If the NLRB still rules for\nan election then it would appear\nto be a \u201cheads management wins,\ntails labor loses\u2019\u2019 regulation, un\nion officials said.\nSince the NLRB decision will\nhave to be based on broad policy\nboth manage\ninterpretations,\nment and labor are watching the\nproceedings closely. The Board's\nruling on the issue will affect\nlabor relations everywhere.\nAttorney Finley pointed out\nthat Retail Associates told the\nNLRB that if the Board calls for\neach\nin\nindividual\nelections\nstore instead of for all three\nstores, it would ask that the en\ntire election petition be dis\nmismissed.\nNot Morally Right\n\u201cNo one can morally justify\nan election in which persons on\nContinued on Page 8\nthe same prospect. Another 1.8\nmillion jobless are ineligible for\nbenefits, he added, and only\nabout 25 per cent of them would\ni benefits under the Administra\ntion plan.\nI He presented statistics show\ning that when unemployed com\npensation was enacted in 1939,\nonly one of the 51 states and ter\nritories Alaska provided\nbenefits lower than 50 per cenf\nof average weekly wages. To\nday only five\u2014Hawaii, Idaho,\nMississippi, North Carolina and\nWyoming pay more than 50\nper cent.\nCan\u2019t Wait on States\nCruikshank emphasized that\nin the face of the \u201cclear\u201d need\nfor supplementation of benefits,\nit is impractical to wait for the\nstates to act.\n\u201cIt is also clear\" need for sup\nplementation of benefits, it is\nimpractical to wait for the states\nto act. I\n\u201cIt is also clear,\u201d he added.\n\u201cthat if federal action stopped at:\nthe point of appropriating funds\nit would have certain damag-1\ning effects on the future sound\nness of the federal-state pro\ngram. I\n\"The federal government is\nnow contemplating action be\ncause it recognizes the inade\nquacy of the state laws, and it\nis therefore essential that it\nshould, at the same time, tie into\nwhatever action it takes legisla\nBy BERNARD STERN\nSteps to halt the recession and help the jobless are the\nthe problems uppermost in people's mind here, Congressman\nThomas (Lud) Ashley has found.\nBut strangely enough, he says, there is no great clamor\nfor a tax cut. Congressman Ashley calls such sentiment \u201cre\nmarkable\u201d in view of the fact\nthat people of this Congres\nsional District are suffering\nI heavy unemployment.\n\u201cThe general feeling I have\nreceived from talking to dozens\nand dozens of people is that they\nfeel a $50 tax cut will be in\neffectual. While they say a large\ntax cut of $100 to $150 would\nbe good, they are concerned of\nthe loss it will mean to the\nFederal Treasury.\n\u201cThe people seem to be taking\na broad view and thinking more\nin terms of the affect on the na\ntional economy. They indicate\nthat what might help them local\nly is meaningless unless the di\nrection of the economy is\nchanged to health and vigor.\u201d I\nPeople Scared, Anxious I\nCongressman Ashley made his\ncomments in an interview with\nthe Union Journal. He is sound\ning out local sentiment during\nthe Easter recess of Congress to\nguide his actions when Congress\nreconvens next week.\nAs far as the people are con\ncerned, he has found doubt, an\nxiety and caution\u2014n o t only\namong the unemployed but those\nwho are still working.\nBusinessmen, he finds, are\n\u201cscared\u201d because unemployment\nis causing their business to de\ncline.\n\u201cTheir one thought is tax\nlegislation to help them and tax\nlegislation which distinguishes\nbetween small and big business.\u201d\nWhile he sees Congress taking\nno immediate action on a tax\ncut, Rep. Ashley believes that it\nwill put top priority on two ma\njor measures:\nI \u2014T h e Kennedy-McCarthy\nbill, of which he is a co\nsponsor. calling for extension\nof unemployment compensa\ntion benefits to 39 weeks and\na uniform scale of benefits and\nlength of payments among i\nstates, and i\n9\u2014A public works program 1\nto get people back to\nwork. In connection with this,\nhe said there is no longer any\nreason to assume there will be I,\nan upturn in view of the De\npartment of Labor's March re\nport on unemployment.\nIn connection with the public\nworks program, Mr. Ashley]\npraised City Council for taking\naction to plan projects which can\nbe put in operation quickly. He\nnoted that there now is a Fede\nl\nral program for long-term, low:\ninterest rates for municipalities'\nand he plans to put details of this)\ntion which would shore up the\nstate systems so that the fed\neral government will not have\nto step in again each time a fu\nture recession threatens.\u201d\n1\nCruikshank asserted that by\n\u201cbold and imaginative\n\u2019\u2019ac\ntion, \u201cwe can turn the threats\nand dangers of this recession,\nand even its accompanying hu\nman suffering, into opportu\nnity to build stronger defenses\n1 for our free economy and our\n1 democratic way of life.\u201d\nSec. of Labor James P. Mitch\nell urged the committee to give\nspeedy approval to the Adminis\ntration\nprogram, emphasizing\nits temporary nature and the\nfact that it would leave state\nlegislation undisturbed. To try\nto \u201cfiddle with\u201d permanent leg\nislation, he declared, would de\ni lay or kill the program.\nNAM Opposes Administration\nThe National Association of\nManufacturers strongly opposed\nthe Administration proposal.\nR. T. Compton, NAM social se\ncurity adviser, called it \u201cone of\nthe most fantastic proposals of\nall time.\u201d\nCompton was one of several\nindustry witnesses who opposed\nthe plan.\nSec-Treas. James B. Carey\nof the AFL-CIO Industrial Un\nion Dept, called the Eisen\nhower program \u201cinadequate\nand little more than a sop to\ntens of thousands unemployed\nREP. ASHLEY\nin the hands of the City Manager\nshortly.\nUpon his return to Washing\nton, Congressman Ashley says\nhe also will push for a bill cut\nting excise taxes as strongly as\nhe can.\nPrices Too High\nAs to prices being too high,\nhe said there are only two ways\nto get them down: Either,\nthrough voluntary action by in\ndustry or by price control.\nHe expressed concern that in\na period of high unemployment,\nprices have failed to drop and\nhe scored the reluctance on the\npart of basic industry and manu\nfacturers to lower prices des\npite the economic situation.\n\u201cThe proposal that UAW Pres\nident Walter Reuther made two\nyears ago to investigate the rela\ntionship between wage, prices\nand profit,\u201d he declared, \u201cis even\nmore necessary today than two\nyears ago.\u201d\nPointing out that consumers\nare paying the \u201ctop dollar in a'\nrecession for food, shelter and\nother necessities of life,\u201d he said\nthat if the Administration had\nbacked a wage-price-profit in\nvestigation and this had been\ndone thoroughly and honestly,\n\u201cpublic sentiment would have\nhalted inflation.\u201d\nRep. Ashley said so far the\nAdministration has been con\ntent to take limited effort to\nstop the recession.\nIts chief action, he said, has\nbeen in the field of monetary\nand fiscal policies to ease money\nand bring down the interest, rate\nthus reversing the tight money\npolicy which caused the reces\nsion.\nNoting that banks have plenty\nof money to lend, he said that\nthe Administration, however,\nhasn\u2019t convinced the banks to\nlower their interest rates.\nI through no fault of their own.\"\nAmerica\u2019s industrial workers,\nhe declared, \u201care more than\ndisappointed\u201d by Eisenhower\u2019s\n'as wail as by his\nproposal\nhalf-hearted program for\nmeeting the recession.\u201d H e\nurged passage of the Kennedy\nMcCarthy bill.\nPres. David J. McDonald of\nthe Steelworkers, hailing efforts\nof Sen. John F. Kennedy (D\nMass.), co-sponsor of the bill, to\nget help for the jobless, wrote\nhim that if any of his Senate col\nleagues doubts the need, to ex\ntend \u201can invitation to visit the\nsteel centers of the nation as our\nguests, so they may study the\nunemployment problem at first\nhand.\u201d\nPossible Relief Plan\nMeantime, the first intimation\nthe Eisenhower Administration\nhas under consideration a relief\nplan for the unemployed came in\ndisclosure that the Social Se\ncurity Administration has circu\nlarized the states to see if they\nhave legislative authority and\nfunds available to administer\nsuch a program should federal\nfunds become available.\nRelief programs are now fi\nnanced by the states. The SSA\nquery stressed that no federal\nbut that it is seeking to find out\nrelief funds are now available,\nwhat legal barriers may be in\nthe way of making U.S. grants\neffective should they be allotted.\nA\nPlease DO N OT Patronize Lasalle\u2019s","height":"26828","width":"19376"}}
